## 1. Model Details

> What model or API is being used? Who built it? What version? What type of
> model — classification, prediction, generation, optimization? When was it
> developed?

The AquaRate mobile app is a predictive model that provides consumers of bottled and packaged water an A-F rating, where A is the best rating and F is the worst, based on water quality factors. The model uses gradient-boosted ensemble, which works by creating many smaller models and combines them to make accurate predictions. This model takes inputs from a particular brand (Total coliform/ E.coli levels, chemcial contaminant levels, mineral content, pH, turbidity, and microplastic presence) and assigns the brand a score from 0-100 which is then converted to a letter grade. Letter grades are assigned as follows: 0-16=F, 17-33=E, 34-50=D, 51-67=C, 68-83=D, 84-100=F. This model was developed in 2025 and is on version 3.0.

---

## 2. Intended Use

> What is the primary task? Who are the intended users? What decisions does
> the system inform? In what context is it deployed?

The main task is to support consumer bottled and packaged water purchase decision by providing an A-F rating based on water quality metrics. The intended users are health-conscious consumers, especially parents of young children and immuno-compromised individuals, in the USA. The intended use case is for consumers to be able to scan the products bar code using the mobile app to see the generated rating so they may decide whih brand of water to purchase, likely while in the store. 

---

## 3. Out-of-Scope Uses

> What should this system NOT be used for? What populations, settings, or
> decisions are outside its design? What misuses are foreseeable?

AquaRate, while it uses real world water quality data to make predictions, it is not backed by any government agency, and has no regulatory authority. The score provided should not be used as a definitive measure of water quality, only an estimate, nor should the rating be treated as a water quality regulation. Purchase decisions made using the rating should not be considered medical advice or a substitute for recommendations provided by a licensed healthcare provider.   

