## 7. Ethical Considerations

> Bias risks, informed consent, privacy, potential harms, equity implications.
> Does this system reproduce or amplify existing disparities? Who bears the
> consequences when it fails?

The mobile app is funded by partnerships with high scoring water brands. This ensures accessibilty, the app is offered for free, however, this partnership may introduce bias as high scoring they may be scanned more often compared to those that are lower scoring. Access may be disporoportionate among communities with poor internet and electricity access, or those without smartphones that can connect to a 5G network, There is potential for harm if users make decissions based on scores that may be over a year old. More current issues may not be captured in the prediction, leaving people to make less well informed health safety decisons. This is more impactful in vulnerable individuals, young children and immuno-compromised people. 

